            <h1 class="mb-3">What is an autism test?</h1>
            <p style="text-align: left;">
                The autism test is one of the modern methods that help diagnose autism spectrum disorder and it is a modified and revised multiple-choice list that asks a series of questions about the child's behavior, and this test is a test for children between the ages of 16 - 30 months.
        
                <div class="container-xl py-5">
                    <h2 class="mb-3">Most of the questions revolve around the following:</h2>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Behavior of the child.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Emotional response.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Ability to imitate.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Use things.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Adaptation and acclimatization.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Visual response.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">- Verbal and non-verbal communication.</p>
                    <p style="text-align: left;">The questions asked in the autism test are answered based on the child's behavior, and based on the results it is decided whether further evaluation is needed.</p>
                </div>
        </div>
        <div class="container-xl py-5">
            <h3 class="mb-3">Criteria for diagnosing autism</h3>
            <h5 style="text-align: left;">
               The criteria used by a psychologist to diagnose autism include:
            </h5>
            <p style="text-align: left;">
                The diagnostic manual, which was released by the American Psychological Association in 2013 and is an approved reference for health care providers to diagnose mental and behavioral conditions, including autism.</p>
            <p style="text-align: left;">
                The International Classification of Medical Diseases, which contains a number of profiles on childhood autism, irrational autism, Asperger syndrome and others.</p>
